/// Bible commentary and study notes
class BibleCommentary {
  static const Map<String, Map<int, String>> _chapterCommentary = {
    // Genesis
    'genesis': {
      1: 'The magnificent account of creation. God speaks the universe into existence over six days, demonstrating His infinite power and wisdom. The repeated phrase "and God saw that it was good" emphasizes the perfection of His creative work. The chapter culminates in the creation of humanity in God\'s image, establishing our unique role as stewards of creation.',
      2: 'A detailed account of the creation of man and woman. The Garden of Eden represents paradise lost through sin, but also points forward to the paradise restored through Christ. The institution of marriage is established here as a divine ordinance.',
      3: 'The fall of humanity. The serpent\'s temptation and Adam and Eve\'s disobedience bring sin and death into the world. Yet even in judgment, God provides hope through the promise of the seed who will crush the serpent\'s head (Genesis 3:15) - the first messianic prophecy.',
      4: 'Cain and Abel - the first murder. This tragic chapter shows how quickly sin spreads after the Fall. Cain\'s jealousy leads to fratricide, demonstrating the destructive nature of sin. Yet God still shows mercy, protecting Cain from immediate death.',
      12: 'God\'s call of Abram marks a pivotal moment in salvation history. The Abrahamic Covenant promises land, descendants, and blessing to all nations through his seed. This covenant forms the foundation for Israel\'s relationship with God and ultimately points to Christ.',
      22: 'The binding of Isaac - Abraham\'s supreme test of faith. This dramatic episode prefigures God the Father\'s willingness to sacrifice His only Son. Isaac carrying the wood parallels Christ carrying the cross. God provides a ram, pointing to the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world.',
    },
    // Exodus
    'exodus': {
      1: 'Israel\'s oppression in Egypt. The book begins in darkness - slavery, genocide, despair. Yet God\'s providence is already at work through the midwives who fear Him more than Pharaoh. The stage is set for deliverance.',
      3: 'The burning bush - God reveals Himself to Moses. "I AM WHO I AM" - the divine name Yahweh, meaning the self-existent, eternal God. This theophany marks the beginning of Israel\'s liberation and establishes Moses as God\'s chosen leader.',
      12: 'The Passover - Israel\'s deliverance through blood. The lamb without blemish, the blood applied to the doorposts, the death passing over - all point to Christ, our Passover Lamb. This foundational event is commemorated annually and finds its fulfillment in the Lord\'s Supper.',
      20: 'The Ten Commandments given at Sinai. God\'s moral law reveals His holy character and exposes human sinfulness. The commandments address our relationship with God (1-4) and neighbor (5-10). They drive us to Christ for salvation and guide believers in righteous living.',
    },
    // Psalms
    'psalms': {
      1: 'The two ways - the righteous and the wicked. This wisdom psalm opens the Psalter by contrasting the blessed person who delights in God\'s law with the wicked who perish. It establishes meditation on Scripture as the path to spiritual prosperity.',
      23: 'The Shepherd Psalm - perhaps the most beloved passage in Scripture. David draws on his experience as a shepherd to illustrate God\'s care for His people. "The Lord is my shepherd" speaks of intimacy, provision, guidance, and ultimate victory over death.',
      51: 'David\'s penitential psalm after his sin with Bathsheba. This profound confession reveals the anatomy of true repentance: acknowledgment of sin, appeal to God\'s mercy, request for cleansing, and desire for restored fellowship. "Create in me a clean heart" remains the cry of every penitent believer.',
      91: 'The psalm of divine protection. Under the shadow of the Almighty, the believer finds refuge from every danger. Satan quoted this psalm to Jesus in the wilderness, but Christ refused to put God to the test. The promises are real, but must be received in faith, not presumption.',
      119: 'The longest chapter in the Bible - a magnificent tribute to God\'s Word. Each of the 22 sections celebrates the beauty, wisdom, and power of Scripture. "Your word is a lamp to my feet and a light to my path" captures the psalmist\'s love for divine revelation.',
    },
    // Isaiah
    'isaiah': {
      53: 'The Suffering Servant - the crown jewel of messianic prophecy. Written 700 years before Christ, it describes His rejection, suffering, and atoning death with remarkable precision. "He was wounded for our transgressions" - the doctrine of substitutionary atonement in its clearest form.',
    },
    // Matthew
    'matthew': {
      1: 'The genealogy of Jesus Christ - the Son of David, the Son of Abraham. Matthew emphasizes Jesus\' royal lineage and includes four women (Tamar, Rahab, Ruth, Bathsheba) showing God\'s grace to sinners and Gentiles. The virgin birth fulfills Isaiah 7:14.',
      5: 'The Beatitudes - the opening of the Sermon on the Mount. Jesus reveals the character of kingdom citizens: poor in spirit, mourning over sin, meek, hungry for righteousness. These blessings invert worldly values and call believers to radical discipleship.',
      6: 'The Lord\'s Prayer and teachings on giving, prayer, and fasting. Jesus exposes hypocrisy and calls for sincere devotion. "Your kingdom come, your will be done" aligns our hearts with God\'s purposes. The chapter ends with the command to seek first God\'s kingdom.',
      28: 'The Great Commission - the risen Christ\'s mandate to His church. "All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me." On this basis, disciples are to be made of all nations through baptism and teaching. Christ\'s presence with His church guarantees success.',
    },
    // John
    'john': {
      1: 'The prologue - "In the beginning was the Word." John establishes Christ\'s deity, pre-existence, and role in creation. The Word became flesh - the incarnation. "Grace and truth came through Jesus Christ" - the full revelation of God.',
      3: 'Jesus and Nicodemus - "You must be born again." The new birth is essential for entering God\'s kingdom. John 3:16, the gospel in a nutshell: "For God so loved the world..." The chapter concludes with John the Baptist\'s testimony to Christ\'s supremacy.',
      10: 'The Good Shepherd discourse. Jesus claims to be the Shepherd who knows His sheep, lays down His life for them, and gives them eternal life. "I and the Father are one" - a clear claim to deity that provoked attempts to stone Him.',
      11: 'The raising of Lazarus - the seventh and greatest sign. "I am the resurrection and the life." Jesus demonstrates His power over death and points forward to His own resurrection. This miracle precipitates the plot to kill Him.',
      20: 'The resurrection - "He is not here; he has risen!" The empty tomb, the appearances to Mary Magdalene and the disciples, Thomas\'s confession "My Lord and my God!" John\'s purpose statement: "These are written that you may believe."',
    },
    // Romans
    'romans': {
      1: 'Introduction and the guilt of humanity. Paul\'s theme: the gospel reveals God\'s righteousness by faith. The chapter ends with a devastating indictment of Gentile sin, setting up the universal need for justification.',
      3: 'All have sinned - both Jews and Gentiles. But now God\'s righteousness has been revealed apart from the law, through faith in Christ. Justification is by grace alone, through faith alone, in Christ alone.',
      8: 'The climax of Romans - life in the Spirit. No condemnation for those in Christ. The Spirit enables holy living and assures adoption. Nothing can separate us from God\'s love in Christ - the golden chain of redemption.',
      12: 'Living sacrifices - the practical outworking of the gospel. Gifts for service, love for others, overcoming evil with good. The Christian life is one of total transformation and dedication to God\'s will.',
    },
    // Revelation
    'revelation': {
      1: 'The revelation of Jesus Christ. John receives this apocalyptic vision while exiled on Patmos. Christ appears in glory among the seven lampstands (the churches). "I am the Alpha and the Omega" - the beginning and the end.',
      21: 'The new heaven and new earth. Death, mourning, and pain are no more. God dwells with His people. The New Jerusalem descends - the fulfillment of all God\'s promises. "Behold, I am making all things new."',
      22: 'The river of life, the tree of life, and the return of Christ. "Behold, I am coming soon!" The book ends with a promise, a warning, and a prayer: "Come, Lord Jesus!"',
    },
  };
  
  /// Get commentary for a chapter
  static String? getChapterCommentary(String bookId, int chapter) {
    final bookCommentary = _chapterCommentary[bookId.toLowerCase()];
    if (bookCommentary == null) return null;
    return bookCommentary[chapter];
  }
  
  /// Get all available commentary books
  static List<String> get availableBooks => _chapterCommentary.keys.toList();
  
  /// Check if commentary exists for a chapter
  static bool hasCommentary(String bookId, int chapter) {
    return getChapterCommentary(bookId, chapter) != null;
  }
  
  /// Get verse explanation (simplified)
  static String? getVerseExplanation(String bookId, int chapter, int verse) {
    // For now, return chapter commentary
    // In future, could have verse-specific notes
    return getChapterCommentary(bookId, chapter);
  }
}
